The establishment rate of Cooperia oncophora related to host age and previous infection was investigated in young calves.				
Parasite-free calves of similar age were kept on a feed pad and divided into multiple groups, based on their age and weight.				
At the start of the experiment one group (A, n=4) received a single challenge dose of 15,000 L3 of a macrocyclic lactone resistant isolate of C. oncophora.				
Two groups (C & D, each n=16) received trickle infections with an ivermectin-susceptible C. oncophora isolate of 2,000 or 10,000 infective stage larvae per week, one group (B, n=16) was kept as an uninfected control.				
At intervals over a period of 11 months two animals from each group were challenged with 15,000 infective stage larvae of an ivermectin-resistant isolate, 25 days later orally treated with ivermectin (0.2 mg/kg; Ivomec) and 5 days later slaughtered for worm counts. 				
On three occasions additional calves (E, n=2) were included with the high trickle infection rate group but also received an ivermectin treatment before challenge to remove the existing worm burden.				
Further calves (F, n=4) of similar age were introduced at the beginning and the end of the experiment to determine the effect of larval age on establishment rate.
